# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: combat-sport
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:combat-sport/10th-planet-jiu-jitsu] In 2003, after earning a black belt under Jean-Jacques Machado, Eddie Bravo opened his first 10th Planet Jiu-Jitsu school in Los Angeles, California.
[src:combat-sport/10th-planet-jiu-jitsu] Bravo's system emphasizes developing students for submission-only grappling competition rather than points, he focused his jiu-jitsu training without the traditional gi, becoming one of the first jiu-jitsu schools in the US to do so.
[src:combat-sport/10th-planet-jiu-jitsu] The idea behind this was to try to implement as many of the techniques as possible in mixed martial arts (MMA) competitions.
[src:combat-sport/10th-planet-jiu-jitsu] Bravo worked for the Ultimate Fighting Championship (UFC) during this time and felt high-level jiu-jitsu practitioners weren't winning as much as they should have, mainly attributing this to them wearing a gi when training jiu-jitsu, but competing in MMA without one.
[src:combat-sport/10th-planet-jiu-jitsu] 10th Planet Jiu-Jitsu has been controversial since its inception; abandoning the gi drew some backlash from other jiu-jitsu schools and there has been a debate as to how many 10th Planet techniques, most notably its iterations of the rubber guard, translate to MMA.
[src:combat-sport/10th-planet-jiu-jitsu] In addition to the original 10th Planet headquarters in Los Angeles, there are over 100 schools worldwide.
[src:combat-sport/10th-planet-jiu-jitsu] Some are established jiu-jitsu training facilities that have adopted the system as an expansion of the art.
[src:combat-sport/10th-planet-jiu-jitsu] In Southern California, affiliate schools include 10th Planet Jiu Jitsu Orange in Orange and 10th Planet Jiu Jitsu Fullerton in Fullerton, both operating from the website 10th Planet Orange & Fullerton.
[src:combat-sport/10th-planet-jiu-jitsu] The style has spread overseas to Ireland, the United Kingdom, Germany, Sweden, Australia, Mexico, Brazil, and Korea.
[src:combat-sport/10th-planet-jiu-jitsu] While 10th Planet Jiu-Jitsu uses the standard Brazilian jiu-jitsu ranking system, its practitioners most commonly train without gi and the belt.
[src:combat-sport/10th-planet-jiu-jitsu] 10th Planet used colored rashguards to help visually denote belt rank.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] The **1906 Intercalated Games** or **1906 Olympic Games** (Greek: Μεσολυμπιάδα, romanized: *Mesolympiada*, lit.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] 'Mesolympics'), held from 22 April 1906 to 2 May 1906, was an international multi-sport event that was celebrated in Athens, Greece.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] It was at the time considered to be part of the series of the Olympic Games, and was referred to as the "Second International Olympic Games in Athens" by the International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] The 1906 Games is noted for its influence on the Olympic tradition and the records broken during these Games are recorded in history, but are no longer considered part of the Olympic records.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] 894 athletes from 20 nations competed in this competition.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] The idea behind the Intercalated Games was to have an Olympics in Greece every four years, but this would be the first and last.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] The idea was not pursued further, and is sometimes termed the "forgotten Games" in the context of the Olympics.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] The next Olympic Games was the 1908 Summer Olympics in London; the next time the Olympic Games returned to Greece was 98 years later in 2004, also in Athens.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] The Intercalated Olympic Games were to be a series of *International Olympic Games* halfway between what is now known as the Games of the Olympiad, old and new.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] This proposed series of Games, intercalated in the Olympic Games cycle, was always to be held in Athens and was to have equal status with the international Games.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] However, the only such Games was held in 1906.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] One reason for the Games in 1906 was to celebrate the tenth anniversary of the 1896 Games.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] The first Intercalated Games had been scheduled by the International Olympic Committee in 1901 as part of a new schedule, where every four years, in between the internationally organised Games, there would be an Intermediate Games held in Athens.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] This was a compromise; after the successful Games of Athens 1896, the Greeks suggested they could organise the Games every four years.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] Since they had the accommodation and had proven they could hold well-organised Games, they received substantial public support.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] However, Pierre de Coubertin, the founder of the International Olympic Committee, opposed this, as he had intended for the first Games to be in Paris in 1900.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] After Paris had lost the première Olympics, De Coubertin did not want the Games to be permanently hosted elsewhere.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] The 1900 Games were overshadowed by the Exposition Universelle, whose organising committee disagreed with De Coubertin's ideas to such an extent that he resigned.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] The organisation of the 1900 Games was haphazard by today's standards, and although some events, such as archery, drew widespread attention, many others were poorly attended.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] Historians' opinions still differ over which events should be considered "Olympic".
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] Consequently, the IOC supported the Greek idea by granting them a second series of quadrennial Games in between the first series.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] This was a departure from the ancient schedule, but it was expected that, if the ancient Greeks could keep a four-year schedule, the modern Olympic Movement could keep a two-year schedule.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] As 1902 was now too close to be logistically workable, and Greece was experiencing political and economic difficulties, the 2nd Olympic Games in Athens were scheduled for 1906, and the IOC as a whole gave Greece full support for the organisation.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] Louis, Missouri were overshadowed by the Louisiana Purchase Exposition, and their organisation was even worse than that of Paris 1900, while travel difficulties meant that only 20% of the athletes were non-American; of these, half were Canadian.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] It was clear the Olympic Movement was in a dire situation and desperately needed to recapture the spirit of Athens 1896.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] It also needed to do so quickly, as to those who did not participate in St.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] Louis, 1908 was a gap of eight years, by which time there would be little, if any, goodwill left for the Games.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] To make matters worse, Rome, the proposed host for 1908, was also planning an exhibition at the same time as the Games, which had been responsible for the failures of Paris and St.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] To the IOC, the 1906 Athens Games being just around the corner would have been a lifeline.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] While De Coubertin still opposed the idea and did not do anything more than his function required of him, the IOC as a whole gave the Greek organising committee full support for the organisation.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] These games offered Greece the huge opportunity to show that it was important to Europe's present and its past.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] It is clear from the beginning that the Olympic Games 1906 became "a grand project far beyond the status of a mere sports meeting", with new structures built to accommodate the events including the restoration of the ancient stadium in Athens.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] The 1906 Games were quite successful: unlike the Games of 1900, 1904 or 1908, they were not stretched out over several months, and unlike 1900 and 1904, they were not overshadowed by an international exposition.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] Their crisp implementation was most likely instrumental in the continued existence of the Games.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] These, along with various other changes, are now accepted as tradition.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] The Games were held from 22 April to 2 May 1906, in Athens, Greece.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] They took place in the Panathenaic Stadium, which had already hosted the 1896 Games and the earlier Zappas Olympics of 1870 and 1875.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] The Games excluded several disciplines that had occurred during the past two Games; it was unclear whether they ought to have been part of the Olympic Games.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] Added to the program were the javelin throw and the pentathlon.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] The 1906 Games is noted for its opening and closing ceremonies, which initiated this tradition.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] The 1908 Games introduced the tradition of the host coming in as the last in the parade also.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] These were the first Games to include an opening ceremony with athletes marching into the stadium as national teams behind their flags.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] King George I officially opened the Games.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] Six thousand schoolchildren took part in the first ever Olympic closing ceremony.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] 854 athletes, 848 men and six women, from 20 countries, competed at the 1906 Intercalated Games.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] 78 events in 14 disciplines, comprising 12 sports, were part of the 1906 Games.
[src:combat-sport/1906-olympics] These medals were distributed but are no longer recognized by the International Olympic Committee.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] The **1908 Summer Olympics** (officially the **Games of the IV Olympiad** and also known as **London 1908**) were an international multi-sport event held in London, England, from 27 April to 31 October 1908.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] The 1908 Games were relocated to London after Italy withdrew from hosting on financial grounds.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Archival research has established that the British Olympic Association was already privately exploring the possibility of London hosting the Games as early as 5 January 1906, three months before the eruption began.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] London was formally confirmed as host on 19 November 1906.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Rome eventually hosted the Games in 1960.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] These were the fourth chronological modern Summer Olympics in keeping with the now-accepted four-year cycle as opposed to the alternate four-year cycle of the proposed Intercalated Games.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] The IOC president for these Games was Baron Pierre de Coubertin.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Lasting a total of 187 days (six months and four days), these were the longest Games in modern Olympics history.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] There were four bids for the 1908 Summer Olympics.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Rome was selected ahead of London, Berlin and Milan.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] The selection was made at the 6th IOC Session in London in 1904.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Italian authorities were preparing to stage the games when Mount Vesuvius erupted on 7 April 1906, devastating the city of Naples.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Funds were diverted to the reconstruction of Naples, so a new host country was required.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] During the Intercalated Games of Athens, still in April 1906, Coubertin approached Lord Desborough about alternatively hosting in London.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Accepting the offer and with a mere 18 months in which to prepare, London was selected for the first time to hold the Games, which were held at White City alongside the Franco-British Exhibition, at the time the more noteworthy event.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] The White City Stadium, built in short time for the Games, held 68,000 people, with full crowds turning up to watch the events.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] The stadium track was three laps to the mile (536.448 metres per lap), as the current standard of 400 metres did not exist until 1962, with a pool (for swimming and diving events) and platforms (for wrestling and gymnastics) in the centre field.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] On the opening day, following the practice introduced at the Intercalated Games of 1906, teams paraded behind national flags.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] The 1908 Olympics also prompted establishment of standard rules for sports, and selection of judges from different countries rather than just the host.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] One reason was the 400 metre race, in which a US runner, John Carpenter, was accused by the British officials of interfering with a British runner.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Part of the problem was the different definition of interference under British and international rules (the events were held under British rules by the decision of the Organising Committee).
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] The officials decided to disqualify Carpenter and ordered a second final race without him.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] British Halswelle was to face the other two finalists.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] These athletes, William Robbins and John Taylor, were both Americans and decided not to participate in the repeat of the final to protest against the judges' decision.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Halswelle was thus the only medallist in the 400 metres.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] The most famous incident of the games came at the end of the marathon.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Dorando Pietri, Italy, began his race at a rather slow pace, but in the second half of the course began a powerful surge moving him into second position by the 32 km (20 mi) mark, 4 minutes behind South African Charles Hefferon.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] When he knew that Hefferon was in crisis, Pietri further increased his pace, overtaking him at the 39 km (24 mi) mark.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] The effort took its toll and with only two kilometres to go, Pietri began to feel the effects of extreme fatigue and dehydration.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] When he entered the stadium, he took the wrong path and when umpires redirected him, he fell down for the first time.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] He got up with their help, in front of 75,000 spectators.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] He fell four more times, and each time the umpires helped him up.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] In the end, though totally exhausted, he managed to finish the race in first place.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Of his total time of 2h 54min 46s, ten minutes were needed for that last 340 metres.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] The American team immediately lodged a complaint against the help Pietri received from the umpires.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] The complaint was accepted and Pietri was disqualified and removed from the final standings of the race.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Since he had not been responsible for his disqualification, Queen Alexandra awarded him a gilded silver cup the next day.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] These Games were the first to include winter events, as had originally been proposed for the Games.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] There were four figure skating events, although held on 28 and 29 October, months after most of the other events.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Oscar Swahn from Sweden, who won the gold medal for running deer shooting, became the oldest Olympic champion of all time, and set another age record by being 72 years and 279 days old during his triumph at the 1920 Summer Olympics in Antwerp, Belgium.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] One of the more unusual shooting events in 1908 was Olympic dueling.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] The discipline, which was an associate event (that is, not official), was performed by facing opponents wearing protective clothing and masks and firing wax bullets.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] American John Taylor was a member of the winning medley relay team, making him the first African-American athlete to win an Olympic gold medal.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Times for the winning team were United States (3:29.4): William Hamilton, 200 metres (22.0); Nathaniel Cartmell, 200 metres (22.2); John Taylor, 400 metres (49.8); and Melvin Sheppard, 800 metres (1:55.4).
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Less than five months after returning from the Olympic Games in London, Taylor died of typhoid fever on 2 December 1908 at the age of 26.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] The budget of the organising committee showed a cost of £15,000; over one-third was labelled "entertainment expense".
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Donations were the major source of revenue; only 28% of income derived from ticket sales.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Total receipts of £21,378 resulted in organisers claiming a profit.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Construction of the White City Stadium, which cost the government about £60,000, was not counted.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Twenty-two sports, representing 110 events in 25 sporting disciplines, were competed.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] A golf tournament had also been planned but it was cancelled a few days before it was scheduled to start.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Swimming, diving, and water polo are considered three disciplines of the same sport, *aquatics*.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] At the time, tug-of-war was part of athletics and the two different football codes (association and rugby (union)) were listed together.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] The International Olympic Committee now considers tug-of-war a separate sport as well as referring to association football as simply "football" and to rugby union as "rugby." In one of seven cycling events (cycling sprint) no medals were awarded.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] The sailing program was open for a total of five sailing classes, but actually only four sailing events were competed.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] The number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Cycle polo, glima and pistol dueling were demonstration sports.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Thirteen sports venues were used for the 1908 Summer Olympics.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] The first winter sports took place at Prince's Skating Club in Knightsbridge.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] White City Stadium served as a precursor to modern stadiums.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] The figure skating events were not held at the next Olympics in Stockholm, but returned for the 1920 Games in Antwerp, heralding the first Winter Olympics that took place in Chamonix in 1924.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] White City was the main venue for the 1934 British Empire Games (known as the Commonwealth Games since 1978) and, before its demolition in 1985, also served as a venue for the 1966 FIFA World Cup.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] The All England Lawn Tennis Club continues to host the Wimbledon championships and is the only venue of the 1908 Games that was used for the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Bisley and Henley served as venues in the 1948 Games when the Olympics returned to London forty years later.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] The 1908 Games featured athletes representing 22 National Olympic Committees.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Finland, Turkey and New Zealand (as part of the team from Australasia) made their first appearance at the Olympic Games.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] The fact that the United Kingdom competed as a single team was upsetting to some Irish competitors, who felt that Ireland should compete on its own, despite being part of the UK at the time.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] They relied on the precedent set by Grand Duchy of Finland, which while being a part of the Russian Empire, competed in London as a separate country.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Fearing an Irish boycott, the authorities changed the name of the team to Great Britain/Ireland, and in two sports, field hockey and polo, Ireland participated as a separate country, winning silver medals in both, although their medals counted towards the UK's tally.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Irish athletes in the United States were not affected by this controversy, and many Irish immigrants to the United States competed for the U.S.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Olympic team as members of the Irish American Athletic Club.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Members of the Irish American Athletic Club won ten of the U.S.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Olympic team's total 23 gold medals, or as many as the nations of France, Germany and Italy combined.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] Britain had more than a quarter of competitors in their team, with 676, compared to 112 on the American team which placed second in the medal standings.
[src:combat-sport/1908-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1908 Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The **2020 Summer Olympics**, officially the **Games of the XXXII Olympiad** and officially branded as **Tokyo 2020**, were an international multi-sport event held from July 23 to August 8, 2021, in Tokyo, Japan, with some of the preliminary sporting events beginning on July 21, 2021.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Tokyo was selected as the host city during the 125th IOC Session in Buenos Aires, Argentina, on September 7, 2013.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Originally scheduled to take place from July 24 to August 9, 2020, the Tokyo Games were postponed until 2021 on March 24, 2020 as a result of the global COVID-19 pandemic, the first such postponement in the history of the Olympic Games (some previous editions had been cancelled but not rescheduled).
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] However, the **Tokyo 2020** branding was retained for marketing purposes.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The events were largely held behind closed doors with no public spectators permitted due to the declaration of a state of emergency in the Greater Tokyo Area in response to the pandemic, the only Olympic Games to be held without official spectators.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] As a consequence of the postponement and the additional challenges caused by the pandemic, the 2020 Games were the most costly ever, with a total expenditure of over $20 billion.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The 2020 Games were the fourth Olympics to be held in Japan, following the 1964 Summer Olympics (Tokyo), the 1972 Winter Olympics (Sapporo), and the 1998 Winter Olympics (Nagano).
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Tokyo became the first city in Asia to hold the Summer Olympic Games twice.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The 2020 Games were the second of three consecutive Olympics to be held in East Asia, following the 2018 Winter Olympics in Pyeongchang, South Korea, and preceding the 2022 Winter Olympics in Beijing, China.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Because of the one-year postponement, Tokyo 2020 is the only Olympic Games to have taken place in an odd-numbered year.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] New events were introduced in existing sports, including 3x3 basketball, freestyle BMX, and mixed-gender team events in a number of existing sports, as well as the return of madison cycling for men and an introduction of the same event for women.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] New IOC policies allowed the host city's organizing committee to add new sports to the Olympic program for just one Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The disciplines added by the Japanese Olympic Committee were baseball and softball, karate, sport climbing, surfing, and skateboarding; the last four of these were making their Olympic debuts, and the last three have remained on the Olympic program.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The United States topped the medal table both by gold (39) and total medals (113), with China finishing second (38 and 89, respectively).
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Host nation Japan finished third, setting a record for the most gold and overall medals won by their delegation at an Olympic Games with 27 and 58, respectively.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Great Britain finished fourth, with 22 gold and 64 total medals.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The Russian delegation, competing as the ROC, finished fifth with 20 gold medals and third in the overall medal count, with 71 medals.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Bermuda, the Philippines, and Qatar won their first-ever Olympic gold medals.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Burkina Faso, San Marino, and Turkmenistan also won their first-ever Olympic medals.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The three candidate cities were Tokyo, Istanbul, and Madrid.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The applicant cities of Baku and Doha were not promoted to candidate status.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The International Olympic Committee (IOC) voted to select the host city of the 2020 Summer Olympics on September 7, 2013, at the 125th IOC Session in Buenos Aires, Argentina, using an exhaustive ballot system.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] None of the candidate cities won more than 50% of the votes in the first round; Madrid and Istanbul were tied for second place, so a runoff vote was held to determine which of the two cities would be eliminated.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The final vote was a head-to-head contest between Tokyo and Istanbul.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Tokyo was selected by 60 votes to 36, gaining at least the 49 votes required for a majority.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In January 2020, concerns were raised about the potential impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on athletes and visitors to the Summer Olympic Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Tokyo organizers and the International Olympic Committee insisted they were monitoring the spread of the disease to minimize its effects on preparations for the Olympics.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The IOC stated that in 2020, their Japanese partners and Prime Minister Shinzo Abe "made it very clear that Japan could not manage a postponement beyond next summer [2021] at the latest".
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Unlike the case for Zika virus during the 2016 Summer Olympics in Rio de Janeiro, SARS-CoV-2 can be transmitted directly between humans, posing tougher challenges for the organizers to counteract the infectious disease and host a safe and secure event.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Also unlike the case for H1N1 "swine flu" during the 2010 Winter Olympics in Vancouver, COVID-19 has a higher fatality rate, and there was no effective vaccine until December 2020.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In a February 2020 interview, Conservative London mayoral candidate Shaun Bailey argued that London would be able to host the Olympic Games at the former 2012 Olympic venues should the Games need to be moved because of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Tokyo Governor Yuriko Koike criticized Bailey's comment as inappropriate.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In early 2021, officials in the US state of Florida offered to host the delayed Games in their state, while John Coates, the IOC vice president in charge of the Tokyo Olympics, said the Games would open even if the city and other parts of Japan were under a state of emergency because of COVID-19.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Estimates by the National Institute of Infectious Diseases and Kyoto University predicted that states of emergency might be required during the Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The reports published at the Ministry of Health experts' panel also showed new patients increasing to 10,000 if the Games were to allow spectators.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Concerns about the pandemic began to affect qualifying events in early 2020.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Some that were due to take place in February were moved to alternative locations to address concerns about traveling to the affected areas, particularly China.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] For example, the women's basketball qualification was played in Belgrade, Serbia, instead of Foshan, China.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The Asia & Oceania boxing qualification tournament, which was originally planned to be held from February 3–14 in Wuhan, China (the location of the original outbreak of the COVID-19 pandemic), instead took place in Amman, Jordan, at the beginning of March.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The third round of the women's football qualification tournament was also affected, as the group matches formerly scheduled to be held in China were moved to Australia.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The European boxing qualification began on March 14, 2020 in London, United Kingdom, but was suspended after two days of competition before being rescheduled for April 2021.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] It eventually resumed in June 2021 but was moved to Paris, France, because of renewed concerns over travel to the UK.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Other qualifying events that were due to take place in March to June 2020 began to be postponed until later in the year and mid-2021 as part of a wider suspension of international sporting competitions in response to the pandemic.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] A multitude of Olympic sports were affected, including archery, baseball, cycling, handball, judo, rowing, sailing, volleyball, and water polo.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Mandatory doping tests were significantly restricted by the COVID-19 pandemic in early 2020.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] European anti-doping organizations raised concerns that blood and urine tests could not be performed and that mobilizing the necessary staff before the pandemic's end would pose health risks.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Despite the need for extensive testing ahead of the Games, the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) stated that public health and safety remained its top priority.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The China Anti-Doping Agency (CHINADA) temporarily suspended testing on February 3, 2020, with plans to resume phased testing later that month.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] By the end of March, anti-doping organizations in the US, France, Great Britain, and Germany had also reduced their testing activities.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] It was subsequently revealed that 23 Chinese swimmers had tested positive for the drug trimetazidine, but were permitted to compete, after CHINADA claimed they had ingested tiny amounts unawares from a kitchen.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Some, including Zhang Yufei, Wang Shun, and Qin Haiyang, went on to win medals.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The affair resulted in deep upset amongst the international athletic community.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The Tokyo Organizing Committee of the Olympic and Paralympic Games (TOCOG) released a statement on March 2, 2020, confirming that preparations for the upcoming Tokyo Olympics were "continuing as planned".
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On March 23, both Canada and Australia indicated that they would withdraw from the Games if they were not postponed by a year.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On the same day, Japanese prime minister Shinzo Abe stated he would support a proposed postponement, citing that ensuring athlete safety was "paramount", and veteran IOC member and former vice president Dick Pound said he expected the Games to be postponed.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On March 24, 2020, 122 days to go for the planned start, the IOC, TOCOG, and prime minister Abe released a joint statement announcing that the 2020 Summer Olympics and Paralympics would be rescheduled to a date "beyond 2020 but not later than summer 2021".
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] They stated that the Games could "stand as a beacon of hope to the world during these troubled times", and that the Olympic flame could become "the light at the end of the tunnel in which the world finds itself at present".
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Prime Minister Abe stated that IOC president Thomas Bach responded "with 100% agreement" to his proposal to delay the Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] For continuity and marketing purposes, it was agreed that the Games would still be branded as Tokyo 2020 despite the change in schedule.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On March 30, 2020, the IOC and TOCOG announced that they had reached an agreement on the new dates for the 2020 Summer Olympics, which would begin with the opening ceremony on July 23, 2021 and end with the closing ceremony on August 8, 2021, still to be held in Tokyo.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The subsequent Winter Olympics in Beijing were scheduled to begin on February 4, 2022, less than six months later.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Shortly before the postponement was confirmed, the IOC and Tokyo 2020 organizers formed a task force named "Here We Go" with the remit to address any issues arising from postponing the Games, such as sponsorship and accommodation.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The organizers confirmed that all athletes who had already qualified for Tokyo 2020 prior to March 24, 2020 would keep their qualification slots.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Health experts expressed concern in April 2020 that the Games might have to be cancelled if the pandemic should persist.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In an interview, the then president of TOCOG and former Japanese prime minister, Yoshirō Mori, asserted that the Games would be "scrapped" if they could not go ahead in 2021.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On April 29, 2020, Prime Minister Abe stated that the Games "must be held in a way that shows the world has won its battle against the coronavirus pandemic".
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Thomas Bach acknowledged in an interview on May 20, 2020, that the job of reorganizing the Tokyo Games was "a mammoth task" and also admitted that the event would have to be cancelled altogether if it could not take place in the summer of 2021.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] However, both Mori and Bach expressed optimism about the Games going ahead.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On January 21, 2021, multiple sources reported that the Japanese government had "privately concluded" that the Games would have to be cancelled.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The government dismissed the claims, stating the reports were "categorically untrue".
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The new Japanese prime minister Yoshihide Suga confirmed on February 19 that the G7 had given unanimous support for the postponed Games to go ahead as scheduled.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Public support for the Games in Japan decreased significantly amid a 2021 surge in COVID-19 cases in the country.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Multiple organizations of medical professionals voiced oppositions to the Games, while an opinion poll in April 2021 saw 40% of participants support the cancellation of the Games and 33% support a second postponement.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In May 2021, 83% of those polled supported the cancellation or postponement of the Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The Tokyo Medical Practitioners Association called for cancellation, stating that hospitals in Tokyo "have their hands full and have almost no spare capacity" in an open letter to the prime minister.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] At least nine out of 47 elected governors supported cancellation of the Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Nearly 37% of Japanese companies surveyed supported cancellation of the Games, and 32% supported postponement.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Kenji Utsunomiya, who had previously run for Governor of Tokyo, collected more than 351,000 signatures on a petition calling for the organizers to "prioritize life" over the Olympics.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Japanese writers Jiro Akagawa and Fuminori Nakamura also called for the Games to be postponed or cancelled.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In July 2021, it was announced that all events in Tokyo were to be held behind closed doors with no spectators due to a new state of emergency.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] A poll by the *Asahi Shimbun* found that 55% of those surveyed supported cancellation of the Olympics, and 68% felt that organizers would not be able to suitably control COVID-19 at the Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Had the Games been cancelled, it would have been the first time since World War II that an Olympic event had been called off and the first Games to be scrapped due to circumstances unrelated to war.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The Tokyo Games were protected through the commercial insurance marketplace Lloyd's of London, by global reinsurers Munich Re and Swiss Re.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The IOC takes out around $800 million of insurance for each Summer Olympics, with the total amount of loss insured for the 2020 Games likely to be more than $2 billion.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The disruption caused by postponing the Games was covered by the insurance policy, with those likely to make claims for their financial losses including local organizers, sponsors, hospitality firms, and travel providers.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Holders of tickets purchased from overseas prior to postponement were entitled to refunds for both Olympic and Paralympic ticket purchases, except for the costs of cancelled hotel bookings.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Although about 600,000 Olympic tickets and 300,000 Paralympic tickets were eligible to be refunded, organizers said they would not release the total costs of the refunds.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The local organizers are responsible for ticket sales and use them to defray the costs of holding the Games; ticket sales were expected to bring in approximately US$800 million, but actual sales were close to zero.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In June 2022, the Tokyo Organizing Committee revealed in the final budget report for the Tokyo Olympics and Paralympics that the cost for the Olympic Games was 640.4 billion yen (US$5.8 billion), which was higher than the cost for the Rio 2016.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The total, final cost of the delayed Games was 1.4 trillion yen (US$13 billion).
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Prior to the Tokyo Olympics being held, many Japanese people were negative about hosting the event, but their attitudes had become more positive toward the end of the Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] However, 64% answered it was good that the Tokyo Games had gone ahead, while 28% answered that they wished the event had not been held.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Of the respondents, 61% were glad the event had been held without spectators, and only 12% said that spectators should have been allowed.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On July 29, less than a week into the Games, journalist Masaki Kubota reported his analysis of the Japanese people's perspective on the Olympics, which he believed was greatly influenced by the change in the way the Japanese news media reported on the Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Once the Tokyo Olympics were underway, followed by the Tokyo Paralympics, there was a sharp increase in COVID-19 cases in Japan, especially those caused by the Delta variant.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On July 26, there were 60,157 cases detected in Japan, breaking the record of 44,961 cases recorded on May 10.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On August 9, one day after the Olympics had ended, daily cases in Japan reached 100,000 for the first time, and new cases continued to increase until the peak on August 23, when 156,931 cases were recorded.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The Tokyo Organizing Committee was originally headed by former Japanese prime minister Yoshirō Mori, but he resigned in February 2021 due to backlash from sexist comments about women in meetings.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Seiko Hashimoto was chosen to succeed him.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Tamayo Marukawa, Minister for the Tokyo Olympic and Paralympic Games, was responsible for overseeing the preparations on behalf of the Japanese government.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The Tokyo Metropolitan Government set aside a fund of ¥400 billion (more than US$3.67 billion) to cover the cost of hosting the Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The Japanese government was considering easing airspace restrictions to allow an increased slot capacity at both Haneda and Narita airports.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] A new railway line was planned to link both airports through an expansion of Tokyo Station, cutting travel time from Tokyo Station to Haneda from 30 to 18 minutes, and from Tokyo Station to Narita from 55 to 36 minutes; funded primarily by private investors, the line would cost ¥400 billion.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The East Japan Railway Company (JR East) was also planning a new route near Tamachi to Haneda Airport.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] There were plans to fund the accelerated completion of the Central Circular Route, Tokyo Gaikan Expressway, and Ken-Ō Expressway, and the refurbishment of other major expressways in the area.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In April 2018, the Tokyo Organizing Committee signed a partnership with the International Labour Organization to ensure decent work in the preparation of and during the 2020 Olympic Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In June 2020, the chief executive of the Organizing Committee, Toshirō Mutō, stated that the committee was exploring options for streamlining the Games to achieve cost savings.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On September 25, the IOC and Tokyo Organizing Committee agreed to a suite of measures to simplify the Games' logistics, including a cut to non-athlete staff, use of online meetings, and streamlined transport, among others.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The committee also outlined areas it would be exploring to maintain the health and safety of all participants.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In February 2012, it was announced that Tokyo's former National Stadium, the central venue for the 1964 Summer Olympics, would undergo a ¥100 billion renovation for the 2019 Rugby World Cup and the 2020 Summer Olympics.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In November 2012, the Japan Sport Council announced it was taking bids for proposed stadium designs.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Of the 46 finalists, Zaha Hadid Architects was awarded the project, which would replace the old stadium with a new 80,000-seat stadium.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] There was criticism of Hadid's design—which was compared to a bicycle helmet and regarded as clashing with the surrounding Meiji Shrine—and widespread disapproval of the costs, even with attempts to revise and "optimize" the design.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In June 2015, the government announced plans to reduce the new stadium's permanent capacity to 65,000 in its athletics configuration (although with the option to add up to 15,000 temporary seats for football) as a further cost-saving measure.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The original plan to build a retractable roof was also abandoned.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] At the end of 2015, in response to public opposition to the increasing costs of the new stadium (which had reached ¥252 billion), the government chose to reject Hadid's design entirely and selected a new design by Japanese architect Kengo Kuma.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Inspired by traditional temples and with a lower profile, Kuma's design had a budget of ¥149 billion.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The changes meant the new stadium could not be completed in time for the 2019 Rugby World Cup as originally intended.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The National Stadium, which was inaugurated on December 21, 2019, was named the Olympic Stadium for the duration of the Tokyo Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In October 2018, the Board of Audit issued a report stating that the total cost of the Olympic venues could exceed US$25 billion.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Of the 33 competition venues in Tokyo, 28 were within 8 kilometers (5 miles) of the Olympic Village, with eleven new venues to be constructed.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On October 16, 2019, the IOC announced plans to re-locate the marathon and racewalking events to Sapporo for heat concerns.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The plans were made official on November 1, 2019, after Tokyo Governor Yuriko Koike accepted the IOC's decision, despite her belief that the events should have remained in Tokyo.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In general, as urban studies scholar Faure notes, "The Tokyo 2020–2021 Games had a relatively moderate impact on the city, compared to previous cases such as Rio and Sochi, or cases in which a major Olympic park was built in Barcelona in 1992, and in Beijing in 2008.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The transport infrastructure has been marginally improved by facilitating access for people with mobility constraints and improving signage in other languages.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Haneda Airport has been expanded, and a hydrogen-powered bus rapid transit system has been introduced.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Several sports and event facilities were built, including the new Olympic Stadium.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In December 2018, the Japanese government chose to ban drones from flying over venues being used for the Olympic and Paralympic Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] A similar ban was also imposed for the 2019 Rugby World Cup, which Japan also hosted.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In January 2020, counterterrorism drills began in different parts where the Games would take place, after intelligence data showed that terrorist groups could have carried out an attack to seek worldwide attention.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In July 2021, prior to the start of the Games, the Japan Coast Guard conducted counterterrorism drills in the Tokyo Bay.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The drill consisted of two inflatable boats trying to stop a suspicious ship from getting to shore.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Applications for volunteering at the 2020 Olympic and Paralympic Games were accepted beginning on September 26, 2018.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] By January 18, 2019, a total of 204,680 applications had been received by the Tokyo Organizing Committee.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Interviews to select the requisite number of volunteers began in February 2019, with training scheduled to take place in October 2019.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Volunteers at the venues were to be known as "Field Cast", and volunteers in the city were to be known as "City Cast".
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] These names were chosen from a shortlist of four from an original 150 pairs of names; the other three shortlisted names were "Shining Blue" and "Shining Blue Tokyo", "Games Anchor" and "City Anchor", and "Games Force" and "City Force".
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The names were chosen by people who had applied to be volunteers at the Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] As of early June 2021, approximately 10,000 out of the 80,000 registered volunteers resigned from the Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Media attributed the rise in pandemic cases as the reason for massive quitting.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] More volunteer assignments were expected to be cancelled due to the spectator ban.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In February 2017, the Tokyo Organizing Committee announced an electronics recycling program in partnership with Japan Environmental Sanitation Center and NTT Docomo, soliciting donations of electronics, such as mobile phones, to be reclaimed as materials for the medals.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Aiming to collect eight tonnes of metals to produce the medals for the Olympic and Paralympic Games, collection boxes were deployed at public locations and NTT Docomo retail shops in April 2017.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] A design competition for the medals was launched in December of that year.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The collection of bronze was completed in November 2018, with the remainder estimated to have been completed by March 2019.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On July 24, 2019 (one year ahead of the originally scheduled opening ceremony), the designs of the medals were unveiled.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The medals for the Olympic and Paralympic Games were designed by Junichi Kawanishi following a nationwide competition.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] A new feature shared with the Paralympic medals is that the ribbons contain one, two, or three silicone convex lines to distinguish gold, silver, and bronze medals, respectively.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The 2020 Summer Olympics podiums were made from plastic waste donated by the Japanese population.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Artist Asao Tokolo was tasked with their design, which was produced using 3D printing technology with 400,000 laundry detergent bottles (24.5 tons) collected from stores and schools across the country for over nine months.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Each podium was constructed from a series of small, 3D-printed cube-shaped modules that were connected to form the three traditional pedestals.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] For the Paralympic Games, they could be transformed into a flat, accessible platform.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The modules were rendered in the same shade of blue as the Tokyo 2020’s logo, and the Olympic rings in front of the podiums were made from recycled aluminum, originally used to form temporary housing for those impacted by the major earthquake in eastern Japan in 2011.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The slogan of the 2020 Summer Olympics torch relay was "Hope Lights Our Way".
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] As determined by a 2009 IOC ruling that banned international torch relays for any future Olympic Games, the 2020 Summer Olympics torch was scheduled to only visit two countries: Greece and host nation Japan.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The first phase of the relay began on March 12, 2020, with the traditional flame lighting ceremony at the Temple of Hera in Olympia, Greece.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The torch then travelled to Athens, where the Greek leg of the relay culminated in a handover ceremony at the Panathenaic Stadium on March 19, during which the torch was transferred to the Japanese contingent.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The flame was placed inside a special lantern and transported from Athens International Airport on a chartered flight to Higashimatsushima in Japan.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The torch was then expected to begin the second phase of its journey on March 20, as it traveled for one week around the three most affected areas of the 2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami—Miyagi, Iwate and Fukushima—where it would go on display under the heading "Flame of Recovery".
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] After leaving Naraha on March 26, the torch would commence its main relay around Japan, incorporating all 47 prefectural capitals.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] After the decision to postpone the Games, the torch was placed again in a special lantern on display in the city of Fukushima for a month.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Then, the lantern was transferred to the Tokyo prefecture, where it was kept safe until the restart of the relay in 2021.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On August 20, 2020, it was announced that the torch relay would begin again in Naraha, Fukushima on March 25, 2021, nearly a year later than originally planned.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The final course of the relay was altered due to concerns regarding public health concerns about gatherings along the route (e.g., the Miyakojima leg was canceled), and the relay was held without spectators due to states of emergency in some regions (e.g., Matsuyama, Hiroshima, Hyōgo, and Okayama).
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The relay ended at Tokyo's National Stadium (Olympic Stadium) on July 23, with tennis player Naomi Osaka lighting the Olympic cauldron at the finale of the opening ceremony.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Participants would be asked to use Japan's COCOA Exposure Notification app and would be tested at least every four days.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Athletes who tested positive would be unable to compete and could be quarantined at a government facility (although leeway would be given in the event of false positives).
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Close contacts would also need to test negative to be cleared for competition.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Athletes would be discouraged from "excessive" celebrations because the actions could spread infected droplets.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The playbooks were criticized in a paper published by *The New England Journal of Medicine* in May 2021, for lacking "scientifically rigorous risk assessment" and failing to "distinguish the various levels of risk faced by athletes".
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The playbook stated that athletes were required to arrive up to five days prior to the start of the competition and to leave within 48 hours of being eliminated from their sport or the conclusion of the competitions.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The IOC recommended the vaccination of athletes against COVID-19 if vaccines were available to them, but this was not a prerequisite for participation and the IOC advised against athletes "jumping the queue" to obtain priority over essential populations.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On May 6, 2021, Pfizer announced it would donate doses of its vaccine to NOCs competing in Tokyo.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Approximately 93,000 athletes and officials were exempt from the quarantine rules upon arriving in Japan, provided they remained in areas separated from the local population.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] With around 300,000 local staff and volunteers entering and exiting these bubbles, and 20,000 vaccine doses allocated for this group, this led to concerns of COVID-19 spreading both during the Games and when teams returned to their countries.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Due to international travel restrictions, the organizing committee announced in March 2021 that no international guests (including spectators, and friends and family members of the athletes) would be allowed to attend the Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] As per existing guidance for spectator sports in Japan, spectators would be asked to refrain from cheering or shouting.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On June 19, 2021, Governor Koike announced that plans for public viewing events for the Games had been scrapped, in order to use the planned venues (such as Yoyogi Park) as mass vaccination sites instead.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On June 21, it was announced that all venues would be capped at a maximum of 10,000 ticketed spectators or 50% capacity, whichever was lower.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On July 2, 2021, the new TOCOG president Seiko Hashimoto warned that there was still a possibility of the Games being held behind closed doors because of rising COVID-19 cases in the country.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Japan's slow vaccination rate was of particular concern.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] A simulation run by the University of Tokyo in May 2021 projected that a new wave of infections could peak in mid-October if the Games went on after the existing state of emergency in Tokyo had expired.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The announcement stated that spectators would still be allowed at events being held outside of Tokyo, subject to the approval by local health authorities and the aforementioned 50%/10,000-spectator limit.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The prefectures of Fukushima, Hokkaido, and Ibaraki announced they would prohibit spectators at events held in the areas.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The opening ceremony was expected to be limited to fewer than 1,000 VIP guests, including IOC representatives and dignitaries, while some events did allow members of other competing delegations to occupy spectator seats as well.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] School students were invited to watch football matches in Ibaraki.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On July 16, it was reported that Bach had asked Prime Minister Suga about the possibility of restrictions on spectators being eased later on if COVID-19 conditions were to improve in Tokyo.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] However, on August 2, Suga announced that all existing state of emergency declarations would be extended through August 31, and be extended to Chiba, Kanagawa, Saitama, and parts of Osaka.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The opening ceremony tickets were expected to range from ¥12,000 to ¥300,000, with a maximum price of ¥130,000 for the finals of the athletics track and field events.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The average ticket price was ¥7,700, with half the tickets being sold for up to ¥8,000.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] A symbolic ticket price of ¥2,020 was expected for families, groups resident in Japan, and in conjunction with a school program.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Tickets would be sold through 40,000 shops in Japan and by mail order to Japanese addresses through the internet.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] International guests, had they been allowed, would have needed to visit Japan during the sales period, or arrange to buy tickets through a third party such as a travel agent.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Tickets went on general sale in Japan in the autumn of 2019 and were expected to be sold globally from June 2020; however, this plan was suspended when the Games were postponed on March 24, 2020.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The Tokyo Organizing Committee confirmed that tickets already purchased would remain valid for the same sessions according to the new schedule and that refunds were also being offered.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On March 20, 2021, it was announced that due to COVID-19-related concerns, no international guests would be allowed to attend the 2020 Olympics or Paralympics.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] This included spectators, as well as the friends and family of athletes.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] All overseas ticketholders would be refunded.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Hashimoto cited uncertainties surrounding international travel restrictions, and goals to preserve the safety of all participants and spectators, and not place a burden on the health care system.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] It was ultimately announced in July that all local spectators were not allowed to attend any events held in Tokyo, Fukushima, and Hokkaido.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] This tournament would have differed significantly from the traditional bi-monthly *Honbasho* tournaments, and featured additional commentary in English and Japanese to help explain the customs and traditions of professional sumo, which are deeply rooted in the Shinto religion.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the original event program was cancelled in April 2020.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] A 10 m (33 feet)-tall puppet named Mocco—inspired by the writings of Naoki Matayoshi, and designed by illustrator Ryōji Arai based on ideas from Tōhoku youth—toured Iwate, Miyagi, and Fukushimai in support of tsunami recovery efforts.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] It was then transported to Shinjuku Gyo-en in Tokyo in mid-July for an exhibition prior to the Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The opening ceremony was held on July 23, 2021, in the Olympic Stadium in Tokyo.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] It included the traditional Parade of Nations.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Emperor Naruhito formally opened the Games, and at the end of the torch relay, the Olympic cauldron was lit by Japanese tennis player Naomi Osaka.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] For the first time in the history of Olympic Games, it was decided that one male and one female from each country would take turns holding flags and serve as two of them.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] This was done by embodying the "Agenda 2020" set during President Bach's term.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] A moment of silence was observed in the opening ceremony for the victims of COVID-19 pandemic, the 2011 earthquake and tsunami, and the Munich massacre.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The event program for the Games was approved by the IOC executive board on June 9, 2017.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] IOC president Thomas Bach stated that their goal was to give the Games "youthful" and "urban" appeal, and to increase the number of female participants.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The Games featured 339 medal events in 33 different sports, encompassing a total of 51 disciplines.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Karate, sport climbing, surfing, and skateboarding made their Olympic debut, while baseball and softball also made a one-off return to the Summer Olympics for the first time since 2008.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] 15 new events within existing sports were also added, including 3×3 basketball, freestyle BMX, and the return of madison cycling, as well as nine new mixed events in several sports (table tennis, archery, judo, shooting (3), triathlon, 4 × 400 m relay running, and 4 × 100 m medley swimming).
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In the list below, the number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The new entrant would join golf and rugby sevens (which would both debut in 2016) as part of the program of 28 "core" sports.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Five sports were shortlisted for removal, including canoe, field hockey, modern pentathlon, taekwondo, and wrestling.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In the final round of voting by the executive board, eight members voted to remove wrestling from the Olympic program.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Field hockey and taekwondo tied in second with three votes each.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The 2013 decision to drop wrestling after Rio 2016 surprised many media outlets, given that the sport's role in the Olympics dates back to the ancient Olympic Games, and was included in the original program for the modern Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] *The New York Times* felt that the decision was based on the shortage of well-known talent and the absence of women's events in the sport.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Out of the shortlist from the IOC vote, wrestling was duly added to the shortlist of applicants for inclusion in the 2020 Games, alongside the seven new sports put forward for consideration.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On May 29, 2013, it was announced that three of the eight sports under consideration had made the final shortlist: baseball/softball, squash, and wrestling.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The other five sports were rejected at this point: karate, roller sports, sport climbing, wakeboarding, and wushu.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] At the 125th IOC Session on September 8, 2013, wrestling was chosen to be included in the Olympic program for 2020 and 2024.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Wrestling secured 49 votes, while baseball/softball and squash received 24 votes and 22 votes, respectively.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] With the adoption of the *Olympic Agenda 2020* in December 2014, the IOC shifted from a "sport-based" approach to the Olympic program to an "event-based" program—establishing that organizing committees may propose discretionary events to be included in the program to improve local interest.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] As a result of these changes, a shortlist of eight new proposed sports was unveiled on June 22, 2015, consisting of baseball/softball, bowling, karate, roller sports, sport climbing, squash, surfing, and wushu.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On September 28, 2015, the Tokyo Organizing Committee submitted their shortlist of five proposed sports to the IOC: baseball/softball, karate, sport climbing, surfing, and skateboarding.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] These five new sports were approved on August 3, 2016, by the IOC during the 129th IOC Session in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, and were included in the sports program for 2020 only, bringing the total number of sports at the 2020 Olympics to 33.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] A total of 56 test events were scheduled to take place in the run-up to the 2020 Olympics and Paralympics.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Two of the events were held in late 2018, but the main test event schedule commenced in June 2019 and was originally due to be completed in May 2020 prior to the start of the Olympics.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Several of the events were incorporated into pre-existing championships, but some had been newly created specifically to serve as Olympic test events for the 2020 Summer Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In February 2019, it was announced that the test events would be branded under the banner "Ready, Steady, Tokyo".
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The Tokyo Organizing Committee was responsible for 22 of the test events, with the remaining events being arranged by national and international sports federations.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The first test event was World Sailing's World Cup Series, held at Enoshima in September 2018.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The last scheduled event was the Tokyo Challenge Track Meet, which was originally due to take place at the Olympic Stadium on May 6, 2020.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p01] All test events originally scheduled to take place from March 12, 2020 onwards were postponed due to COVID-19, with the test event calendar to be reviewed during the preparations for the rescheduled Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The Republic of Macedonia has competed under the provisional name "Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia" in every Summer and Winter Games since its debut in 1996 because of the disputed status of its official name.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The naming disputes with Greece ended in 2018 with the signing of the Prespa agreement, and the country was officially renamed North Macedonia in February 2019.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The new name was immediately recognized by the IOC, although the Olympic Committee of North Macedonia (NMOC) was not officially adopted until February 2020.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The NMOC sent a delegation to the 2020 Winter Youth Olympics in January 2020, but the Tokyo Games were North Macedonia's first appearance at the Summer Olympics under its new name.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Since competing as Swaziland ten times at the Summer and Winter Olympics, Eswatini made its debut under that name after the renaming of the country by the king in 2018.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] As a result of the ban, WADA planned to allow individually cleared Russian athletes to take part in the 2020 Summer Olympics under a neutral banner, as instigated at the 2018 Winter Olympics, but they would be excluded from team sports.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The head of WADA's Compliance Review Committee, Jonathan Taylor, stated that the IOC would not be able to use the "Olympic Athletes from Russia" (OAR) designation as it did in 2018, emphasizing that neutral athletes could not be portrayed as representing a specific country.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Russia later filed an appeal to the Court of Arbitration for Sport (CAS) against WADA's decision.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] After reviewing the case on appeal, CAS ruled on December 17, 2020 that the penalty placed on Russia be reduced.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The ruling does allow for "Russia" to be displayed on the team uniform—although it should be no more visible than the "Neutral Athlete/Team" designation—as well as the use of the Russian flag's colors within the uniform's design.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] On February 19, 2021, it was announced that Russia would compete under the acronym "ROC" after the name of the Russian Olympic Committee, although the name of the committee itself in full could not be used to refer to the delegation.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The ROC team would be represented by the flag of the Russian Olympic Committee.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] On April 6, 2021, North Korea announced it would not participate in the 2020 Summer Olympics because of COVID-19 concerns.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] This marked North Korea's first absence from the Summer Olympics since 1988.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] In September, a month after the games concluded, the Olympic Committee of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea was banned from participation in the 2022 Winter Olympics, after they failed to participate in the Tokyo Olympics.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] On July 21, 2021, Guinea announced it would not be sending a delegation to the Tokyo Olympics, allegedly due to COVID-19 concerns, though media outlets suggested financial considerations may have been the real motivating factor.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Guinea later reversed the decision and confirmed it would be participating.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The following 206 teams qualified (including the 104 universality places guaranteed in athletics, under which all 206 NOCs may send competitors regardless of qualification).
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The 2020 schedule by session was approved by the IOC Executive Board on 18 July 2018, with the exception of swimming, diving, and artistic swimming.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] A more detailed schedule by event was released on 16 April 2019, still omitting a detailed schedule for the boxing events.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] A detailed boxing schedule was released in late 2019.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The original schedule was from 22 July to 9 August 2020.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] To postpone the Olympics until 2021, all events were delayed by 364 days (one day less than a full year to preserve the same days of the week), giving a new schedule of 21 July to 8 August 2021.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Naoki Satō composed the music for the medal ceremonies.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Satō chose not to employ any musical elements distinctive to Japan "because victory ceremonies are for athletes from around the world" and he wanted all medalists to "feel at ease" when taking their places on the podium, regardless of their nationality.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The bouquets presented to the athletes came from regions affected by the 2011 earthquake and tsunami.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The individual flowers were selected to represent the prefectures of Miyagi, Fukushima, Iwate, and Tokyo.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Per the historical precedent of swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics in Beijing and figure skating at the 2018 Winter Olympics in Pyeongchang, swimming finals were held in the morning to allow live primetime broadcasts in the Americas.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] NBC paid substantial fees for rights to the Olympics, so the IOC has allowed NBC to influence event scheduling to maximize US television ratings when possible.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] On May 7, 2014, NBC agreed to a US$7.75 billion contract extension to air the Olympics through the 2032 Games, with the company being one of the IOC's major sources of revenue.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Japanese broadcasters were said to have criticized the decision, as swimming is one of the most popular Olympic events in the country.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The official emblems for the 2020 Olympics and Paralympics were unveiled on April 25, 2016; designed by Asao Tokolo, who won a nationwide design contest, it takes the form of a ring in an indigo-colored checkerboard pattern.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The design was meant to "express a refined elegance and sophistication that exemplifies Japan".
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The checkered design resembles a pattern called *ichimatsu moyo* that was popular during the Edo period in Japan from 1603 to 1867.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The designs replaced a previous emblem that had been scrapped after allegations it plagiarized the logo of the Théâtre de Liège in Belgium.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The Games' bid slogan was *Discover Tomorrow* (Japanese: 未来（あした）をつかもう, romanized: *Ashita o tsukamō*).
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] While *ashita* literally means "tomorrow", it is intentionally spelled as *mirai*, "future".
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The official slogan *United by Emotion* was unveiled on February 17, 2020.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The official mascot of the 2020 Summer Olympics was Miraitowa, a figure with blue-checkered *ichimatsu moyo* patterns inspired by the Games' official emblem.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Its fictional characteristics include the ability to teleport.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Created by Japanese artist Ryo Taniguchi, the mascots were selected from a competition process which took place in late 2017 and early 2018.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] A total of 2,042 candidate designs were submitted to the Tokyo Organizing Committee, which selected three pairs of unnamed mascot designs to present to Japanese elementary school students for the final decision.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The results of the selection were announced on February 28, 2018, and the mascots were named on July 22, 2018.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Miraitowa is named after the Japanese words for "future" and "eternity".
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The mascots were expected to help finance the Tokyo Games through merchandizing and licensing deals.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Alongside the main *Emblem blue*, five other colors were used in the branding of the 2020 Games: *Kurenai red*, *Ai blue*, *Sakura pink*, *Fuji purple*, and *Matsuba green*.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] These five traditional colors of Japan were used as sub-colors to create points of difference in the color variations.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Several controversial issues occurred during preparations for the Tokyo Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] There were allegations of bribery in the Japanese Olympic Committee's (JOC) bid and of plagiarism in the initial design for the Games' logo.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] On December 10, 2018, the French financial crimes office began an investigation of Tsunekazu Takeda, the president of the Japanese Olympic Committee, concerning a 2013 scheme to obtain votes from African IOC members in support of Tokyo as host for the 2020 Olympics over Istanbul or Madrid.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] In March 2020, a Japanese businessman admitted to giving gifts, including cameras and watches, to IOC officials to lobby for their support of Tokyo's bid to host the Olympic Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The official emblems of the Tokyo Olympics and Paralympics, designed by Kenjirō Sano, were unveiled in July 2015 but were withdrawn and replaced following plagiarism accusations.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The lawsuit by Olivier Debie, who claimed his logo design was copied, was later dropped, with the designer citing escalating legal costs.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Mass logging for construction of the Olympic venues received international criticism.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] In February 2018, the Olympics Organizing Committee admitted that 87% of plywood panels used to build the new national stadium was sourced from endangered rainforests.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Portions of the Games were scheduled for locations impacted by the 2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami, and the subsequent Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The hosting of events in these locations was promoted as a means of furthering recovery in the regions, with the Games sometimes being promoted as the "Recovery Olympics".
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] However, the organization of events in these regions faced criticism; Fukushima is considered safe by the World Health Organization and the United Nations, although scientific studies on the safety of the area are still disputed.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Some Tōhoku residents questioned the decision to use the region as a host site, arguing that preparations for the Games slowed down recovery efforts, and that the region lost workers to projects associated with the Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Use of the flag in international sporting events such as the Olympic Games is controversial because it was used for waging aggressive war against many countries in Pacific regions, including the attack on Pearl Harbor.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] According to the Associated Press, the IOC issued a statement in response to South Korea's request, saying, "sports stadiums should be free of any political demonstration.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] In February 2021, the TOCOG president Yoshirō Mori resigned, after facing both domestic and international criticisms over his sexist remarks.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The previous conduct of the new president, Seiko Hashimoto, had also drawn criticisms, leading her to comment "I regret it and think I should be careful" on one of the accusations.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The head creative director for the opening and closing ceremonies, Hiroshi Sasaki, resigned in March 2021, after making demeaning comments about Naomi Watanabe.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The composer for the opening ceremony, Keigo Oyamada, resigned days before the ceremony after growing criticism of his past bullying of people with apparent disabilities, such as Down syndrome.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] On July 16, a week before the opening ceremony, TOCOG announced their support of Oyamada as a composer and vowed not to change his selection for the ceremonies, but growing criticism forced him to announce his resignation on July 19.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Officials reported that by early June 2021, about 10,000 of the 80,000 registered volunteers had quit.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] "There's no doubt that one of the reasons is concern over coronavirus infections," the chief executive of the Organizing Committee said, also stating he did not believe this would impact the operation of the Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] On July 23, hundreds of anti-Olympic protestors gathered outside the Japan National Stadium before the opening ceremony.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Security guards blocked reporters from leaving the stadium to interview protestors.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] In total, more than 60,000 police were mobilized for security during the Games, and police were regularly deployed to break up public displays of protest, including tackling protestors on their way to join the anti-Olympic protest in Sendagaya during the closing ceremony on September 5, 2021.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Writing for *The Conversation*, Olympic scholar MacIntosh Ross raised concerns about the relationship between the IOC and WHO, suggesting the organizations showed a lack of concern for the health of Japanese citizens and Olympians.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Still, the story that Japan—or at least the LDP—wanted to tell, of a newly reborn and 'normal' Japan (re-)entering the world stage remained untold.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] A number of controversies arose during the Games, most notably the attempted repatriation on August 1 of Belarusian sprinter Krystsina Tsimanouskaya, allegedly for her criticism of the national sports authorities and team management.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Refusing to return to Belarus, over fears for her safety, Tsimanouskaya sought assistance from the IOC and traveled to Warsaw, Poland, on August 4 after being granted a humanitarian visa by Tokyo's Polish Embassy.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Near the end of the Olympics, it was reported that Australian athletes had damaged the village rooms before departure, leaving a pool of vomit on the floor, damaged beds, and a hole in the wall.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Australian rugby Olympians also reportedly became drunk on the flight to Sydney, leaving vomit in the plane bathroom and receiving complaints from other passengers.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Team Australia chief Ian Chesterman played down the incidents, and said the Olympians would not be punished.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Algerian judoka Fethi Nourine and his coach Amar Benikhlef were suspended for 10 years by the International Judo Federation after Nourine refused to fight an Israeli athlete at the Olympics.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Nourine said his political support for the Palestinians in the Israeli–Palestinian conflict made it impossible for him to compete against Israeli athletes.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Sudan's Mohamed Abdalarasool also withdrew from the competition to avoid the Israeli athlete.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] After the Olympics concluded, New Zealand diving judge Lisa Wright revealed that during the diving events, Zhou Jihong, Vice President of FINA from China, allegedly launched a verbal tirade at Wright at the conclusion of the men's 10 m platform final.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Wright alleged that Zhou verbally abused her for underscoring Chinese divers.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Diving New Zealand subsequently complained about the incident to FINA's Ethics Panel.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] As a result, Zhou was ordered by a FINA Ethics Panel decision to write a letter of apology to Wright.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] A recommendation was also made by the Ethics Panel to disestablish Zhou's position as Diving Bureau Liaison for FINA.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The FINA Ethics Panel stated that the incident during the men's platform final was "unfortunate" and led to a "misunderstanding mixed with misjudgement" between Wright and Zhou.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Latimer claimed that Zhou's behavior was tarnishing the reputation of international diving and that she was acting in the interests of China rather than international diving as a whole.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Subsequent to Latimer's complaint, video evidence emerged online showing Zhou coaching Chinese divers during competition sessions at the Olympics, a behavior considered unethical given her supposedly neutral role as a FINA Vice President and Diving Bureau Liaison.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The Olympic Games Tokyo 2020 reached a global broadcast audience of 3.05 billion people, according to independent research conducted on behalf of the International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Sony and Panasonic partnered with NHK to develop broadcasting standards for 8K resolution television, with a goal to release 8K television sets in time for the 2020 Summer Olympics.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] In early 2019, Italian broadcaster RAI announced its intention to deploy 8K broadcasting for the Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] NHK broadcast the opening and closing ceremonies, and coverage of selected events in 8K.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Telecom company NTT Docomo signed a deal with Finland's Nokia to provide 5G-ready baseband networks in Japan in time for the Games.
[src:combat-sport/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Audio manufacturer Audio-Technica was selected by NBC Olympics, a division of the NBC Sports Group, to provide microphone and headphone equipment for production of the Games in partnership with the IOC.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Modern academic fencing, the *Mensur*, is neither a duel nor a sport.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] It is a traditional way of training and educating character and personality; thus, in a *Mensur* bout, there is neither winner nor loser.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] In contrast to sports fencing, the participants stand their ground at a fixed distance.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] At the beginning of the tradition, duelers wore only their normal clothing (as duels sometimes would arise spontaneously) or light-cloth armor on the arm, torso, and throat.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] In recent years, fencers are protected by mail or padding for the body, fencing arm, fencing hand (gauntlet) and the throat, completed by steel goggles with a nose guard.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] In Austria and Switzerland, a nose guard is uncommon.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Opponents fence at arm's length and stand more or less in one place, while attempting to hit the unprotected areas of their opponent's face and head.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Flinching or dodging is not allowed, the goal being less to avoid injury than to endure it stoically.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Two physicians are present (one for each opponent) to attend to injuries and stop the fight if necessary.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] The participants, or *Paukanten*, use specially developed swords.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] The so-called *Mensurschläger* (or simply *Schläger*) exists in two versions.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] The most common weapon is the *Korbschläger* with a basket-type guard.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Some universities use the so-called *Glockenschläger* (lit.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] 'bell hitter'), which is equipped with a bell-shaped guard.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] These universities are Leipzig, Berlin, Greifswald, Dresden, Tharandt (in the Forestry College, which is now part of Technische Universität Dresden), Halle on the Saale, Frankfurt-an-der-Oder, and Freiberg.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] In Jena, both *Korbschläger* and *Glockenschläger* are used.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] *Studentenverbindungen* from some western cities use *Glockenschläger* because their tradition had its origin in one of the eastern universities but moved to West Germany after World War II.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] The scar resulting from a hit is called a "smite" (German: *Schmiss*), and was seen as a badge of honour, especially in the second half of the 19th century and the first half of the 20th.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Nowadays the presence of scars usually indicates a mistake and therefore are no longer considered especially dignified.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Today, it is not easy for an outsider to identify Mensur scars due to better medical treatment.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Also, the number of mandatory Mensuren was reduced in the second half of the 20th century.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Most Mensur scars are located on the left temple of the forehead.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Scars on the cheek and chin are rather uncommon today and sometimes due to accidents.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Starting in Spain at the end of the 15th century, the dueling sword (rapier) became a regular part of the attire of noblemen throughout Europe.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] In the Holy Roman Empire, this became usual among students, as well.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Brawling and fighting were regular occupations of students in the German-speaking areas during the early modern period.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] In line with developments in the aristocracy and the military, regulated duels were introduced to the academic environment, as well.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] The basis of this was the conviction that being a student meant being something different from the rest of the population.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Students wore special clothes, developed special kinds of festivities, sang student songs, and fought duels, sometimes spontaneously (so-called *rencontre*, French "meeting" or "combat"), sometimes according to strict regulations called *comment* (French "how").
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] The weapons used were the same as those employed in civilian dueling, being at first the rapier and later the smallsword (court sword, dress sword, French: *épée de cour*, German: *Kostümdegen, Galanteriedegen*), which was seen as part of the dress and always at hand as a side arm.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Student life was quite unsafe in these years, especially in the 16th and 17th centuries during the Reformation wars and the Thirty Years' War (1618–1648), when a major part of the German population was killed.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Public life was brutal and students killing each other in the street was not uncommon.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] A major step towards civilization was the introduction of the "regulated" duel, of which the first recordings exist from the 17th century.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] The fight was not decided on the spot, but the time and location were appointed and negotiations were done by officials.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] A so-called *Kartellträger* did the arrangements and a "second" represented the interests of the fighter during the duel and could even give physical protection from illegal actions.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] A kind of referee was present to make decisions, and eventually, the practice of having an attending doctor became normal so as to give medical help in case of an injury.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] At the end of the 18th century (after the French Revolution), wearing weapons in everyday life fell out of fashion and was more and more forbidden, even for students.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] This certainly reduced the number of spontaneous duels dramatically.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] The regulated duel remained in use, though still forbidden.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] The foil was invented in France as a training weapon in the middle of the 18th century to practice fast and elegant thrust fencing.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Fencers blunted the point by wrapping a foil around the blade or fastening a knob on the point ("blossom", French: *fleuret*).
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] In addition to practising, some fencers took away the protection and used the sharp foil for duels.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] German students took up that practice and developed the *Pariser* ("Parisian") thrusting small sword for the *Stoßmensur* ("thrusting mensur").
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] After the dress sword was abolished, the *Pariser* became the only weapon for academic thrust fencing in Germany.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Since fencing on thrust with a sharp point is quite dangerous, many students died from their lungs being pierced (*Lungenfuchser*), which made breathing difficult or impossible.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] However, the counter-movement had already started in Göttingen in the 1760s.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Here the *Göttinger Hieber* was invented, the predecessor of the modern *Korbschläger*, a new weapon for cut fencing.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] In the following years, the *Glockenschläger* was invented in east German universities for cut fencing as well.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Thrust fencing (using *Pariser*) and cut fencing (using *Korbschläger* or *Glockenschläger*) existed in parallel in Germany during the first decades of the 19th century—with local preferences.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Thrust fencing was especially popular in Jena, Erlangen, Würzburg, and Ingolstadt/Landshut, two towns where the predecessors of LMU Munich were located.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] The last thrust *Mensur* is recorded to have taken place in Würzburg in 1860.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Until the first half of the 19th century, all types of academic fencing can be seen as duels, since all fencing with sharp weapons was about honour.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] No combat with sharp blades took place without a formal insult.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Compared to pistol duels, these events were relatively harmless.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] The fight regularly ended when a contestant received a wound at least one inch long that produced at least one drop of blood.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] It was not uncommon for students to have fought approximately 10 to 30 duels of that kind during their university years.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] The German student Fritz Bacmeister is the 19th-century record holder, due to his estimated 100 mensur bouts fought in Göttingen, Jena, and Würzburg between 1860 and 1866.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] In the 20th and 21st century it was Alexander Kliesch (Landsmannschaft Brandenburg Berlin) with 70.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] For duels with nonstudents, e.g., military officers, the "academic sabre" became usual, apparently derived from the military sabre.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] It was a heavy weapon with a curved blade and a hilt similar to the *Korbschläger*.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] During the first half of the 19th century and some of the 18th century, students believed the character of a person could easily be judged by watching him fight with sharp blades under strict regulations.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Academic fencing was more and more seen as a kind of personality training by showing countenance and fairness even in dangerous situations.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Student corporations demanded their members fight at least one duel with sharp blades during their university time.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] The problem was that some peaceful students had nobody to offend them.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] The solution was a kind of formal insult that did not actually infringe honour, but was just seen as a challenge for fencing.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] In the long term, this solution was unsatisfying.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Around 1850, the *Bestimmungsmensur* (German *bestimmen* means "ascertain", "define" or "determine") was developed and introduced throughout Germany.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] This meant the opponents of a *Mensur* were determined by the fencing official of their corporations.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] These officials were regularly vice-chairmen (*Consenior*) and responsible for arranging *Mensur* bouts in cooperation with their colleagues from other corporations.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Their objective was to find opponents of equal physical and fencing capabilities to make the event challenging for both participants.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] That is the way it is still done today and is the concept of the *Mensur* in the modern sense of the word.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Before the Communist revolution in Russia and before World War II, academic fencing was known in most countries of Eastern Europe, as well.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] By the end of the 19th century, the duelling form evolved into the modern Mensur.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] During the times of the Third Reich, the national socialist leadership initially legalized the practice in 1935, but would again forbid it 1937 as part of the broader crackdown on independent student organizations, which included the *Studentenverbindung*.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] As Nazi pressure increased and fraternities were forced to officially suspend their activities, so-called comradeships were founded.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] These provided means for practising and organising the *Mensur* among former fraternities while remaining undetected to the Nazi secret police.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] One such example was the SC-Comradeship *Hermann Löns* initiated by members of the Corps Hubertia Freiburg and other fraternities in Freiburg, Germany.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] There, fencing Mensur "duels" continued and even intensified from 1941 on, with over 100 of such duels happening during World War II in Freiburg alone.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Following the war, most of the formerly suspended fraternities were reactivated and resumed the traditions of Mensur fencing if they had not continued throughout the time of Nazi rule.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Today, the Mensur is practised by about 400 traditional *Studentenverbindung* fraternities in Germany, several of the *Corps*, *Burschenschaften*, *Landsmannschaften*, *Turnerschaften*, and *Sängerschaften*.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] *Menzura*, as the *Mensur* is known in Poland, is still practised, although its popularity has declined since the end of World War II.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] It is also still known in a few other European countries, though there, protective equipment use is extensive and duelling scars are almost unheard of.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] American traveller Mark Twain devoted several chapters of *A Tramp Abroad* (1880) to Heidelberg students' fencing.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] In *Three Men on the Bummel* (1900), Jerome K.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] Jerome devoted a chapter to German student life, and describes the "German Mensur" in detail.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] While much of the book has a tone of admiration for the German people, he expressed extreme disapproval for this tradition.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] In George MacDonald Fraser's *Royal Flash* (1970), the protagonist Harry Flashman is scarred with a *Schläger* as part of his disguise as a Danish prince.
[src:combat-sport/academic-fencing] In the James Bond books by Ian Fleming, the supervillain Ernst Stavro Blofeld has a duelling scar below his eye.
[src:combat-sport/arb-martial-art] ARB's origin as a military-applied martial art dates back to 1979 when the city of Kaunas (the settlement Gaižiūnai, military unit no.
[src:combat-sport/arb-martial-art] 42235) held the first championship for Airborne troops on the sports base of the 7th Guards Airborne Division.
[src:combat-sport/arb-martial-art] Since then, the Airborne troops' ARB championships have been held annually.
[src:combat-sport/arb-martial-art] ARB was created by experts and enthusiasts of physical preparation and was played as a sport of the Soviet Army.
[src:combat-sport/arb-martial-art] It was also successfully introduced into the Soviet army to train soldiers.
[src:combat-sport/arb-martial-art] Carrying out of the first championship on ARB would not have been possible without long-term practice and experiments with various kinds of single combat.
[src:combat-sport/arb-martial-art] Black belt-rated sportsmen and prize-winners of competitions in sambo, boxing, wrestling, judo and other fighting sports were carefully selected to participate in a game of ARB.
[src:combat-sport/arb-martial-art] Methodical work of fighters and commanders, has also impulsed to the origin of the martial art which is nowadays widely known under the name "Army Hand-to-Hand Combat".
[src:combat-sport/arb-martial-art] At that point in time (the beginning of the 1970s) actual training of regular soldiers for hand-to-hand combat was named as "the Program of preparation of instructors in sports and special receptions of a landing".
[src:combat-sport/arb-martial-art] A distinctive part of ARB that sets it apart from other full contact single combat martial arts is the possibility of finishing with the opponent on hands and feet from a standing position.
[src:combat-sport/arb-martial-art] The opponent may call "Stop", as some kicks on the head of the opponent may not be protected by a helmet, and can lead to heavy damages that interrupt the match immediately.
[src:combat-sport/arb-martial-art] Blows of the opponent by a foot in a head is a knock-down to the fighter who has performed such a blow.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] With over 300,000 active members in over 21 countries —800 schools and 120,000 members in the United States alone—it is one of the largest taekwondo organizations in the world.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Founder Haeng Ung Lee received his first degree black belt in 1954 and began teaching taekwondo to Korean army members.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Air Force base near Seoul and began teaching American servicemen, including an officer named Richard Reed.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] The two met in 1961 and Reed would inspire Lee to move to Omaha, Nebraska and open his first U.S. taekwondo school a year later.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] The American Taekwondo Association was formed in 1969, and its permanent headquarters was established in Little Rock, Arkansas, in 1977.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] The first World Championships tournament was begun in 1990, where H.U.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Lee was the first to receive the title of Grand Master.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] To "serve as a memorial to [his] work, dedication and commitment," the H.U.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Lee International Gate and Garden was erected in 2009 in front of ATA headquarters.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Songahm Taekwondo is the style of martial arts practiced at ATA affiliated schools.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] *Songahm* means "Pine Tree and Rock." According to the organization, the term Songahm itself represents "Evergreen strength the year round, long life and a symbol of unchanging human loyalty" as represented by the pine tree and the rock.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Soon Ho Lee gave the name, Songahm, and its meaning to his brother, Haeng Ung Lee years before H.U.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] In the *ATA*, the student is compared to a growing pine tree, from a seed (white belt) to a massive tree (black belt).
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] The ATA has a legacy program that allows students to work as leaders and instructors in junior classes.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] This helps the trainee instructors become qualified taekwondo instructors and earn the ATA title of Certified Instructor.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] ATA Martial Arts uses a rank system divided into two series: the colored belt series, and the black belt series.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Each series has nine ranks, the purpose of which are to establish a chain of command and measurement of student progress.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] The increased number of smaller goals provided by nine levels of colored belt rank was designed for added motivation by giving many short term goals to achieve and eliminating having to remain in a single color for several months at a time.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] The rank of 9th degree black belt is the highest conventional ranked Black Belt.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Obtaining the rank denotes one as a "Grand Master".
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] The honorary rank of 10th degree black belt, also known as "Eternal Grand Master", was bestowed upon Haeng Ung Lee, the founder of the ATA, following his death in 2000.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] The rank was sponsored and awarded by Grand Masters of other major martial arts, many of whom attended Haeng Ung Lee's funeral.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Each rank from white belt to second degree black belt may be held either as a Recommended (R) or Decided (D) rank.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] The "decided" rank is a half step above the "recommended" rank.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Some schools denote this rank with a piece of black tape around the end of the belt hanging on the student's right side, or a black strip along the center of the belt.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] At promotional rank testings, students may receive a "Full Pass," "Half Pass," or "No Change." For recommended black belt ranks, the student is required to successfully pass testing for their next decided rank within 6 months of achieving their current recommended rank.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Failure to do so would result in the student being returned to their next lowest decided rank (I.E. a 2nd degree recommended would be returned to 1st degree decided).
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Upon attaining the rank of 6th degree black belt, the next step is earning the mantle of "Master Instructor." To earn this title the 6th degree must undergo a rigorous application and testing process lasting one year.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Similarly, there is a minimum period of a year between earning a 7th degree and the Senior Master title, earning an 8th degree and the Chief Master title, and earning a 9th degree and the Grand Master title.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Before 2015, there was only one Grand Master at a time; however, after the promotion of multiple Grand Masters the title "Presiding Grand Master" is now used to distinguish the Grand Master chosen from the others to be in charge of the ATA.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Licensed locations often utilize full-length color stripes in belts to signify the various rank.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] White, Orange, Yellow, Camo, Green, Purple, Blue, Brown, Red and Black stripes run along the center of the belt from one end to the other.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] These locations may also utilize black wrapped stripes around one end to signify "time-in-grade" or "Degree of Rank" with advancement to the next belt color after obtaining five (5) stripes or 'degrees'.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] A form (poome sae) is a series of kicks, blocks and other techniques put together in a set pattern.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] The pattern becomes more complex as students progress through the ranks.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] For example, the 9th grade white belt form contains eighteen moves.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] The 5th grade green belt form has 34 moves, the 1st degree black belt form has 81 moves, and the 9th degree black belt form has 99 moves.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] If all of the forms (eighteen in all) are done in sequence, they form the pattern of a nine pointed star (eight outer points plus a center point) referred to as the Songahm Star.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] According to the ATA, when the outer points of the Songahm star are connected, they form a circle which exemplifies complete balance.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] The ATA teaches that forms create a contextual application for new material learned at each belt level.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] One steps are a short combination of blocks, strikes and kicks that serve as a precursor to free sparring.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] The ATA aims to teach students to put moves into combinations, focus their techniques at a specific target, learn distancing and gain self-control.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] There are three specific one steps for each belt level starting at white belt and ending with green.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] As with the forms, the one steps become more complex as a student progresses in rank.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Students and instructors alike each wear a traditional white dobok with the appropriate belt and additions.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Each dobok has on the right breast an ATA shield patch with a school or club-specific patch on the left.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] On the back of the uniform, instructors and trainee instructors are required to have the word "TAEKWONDO" arching over a red and blue ATA patch.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Underneath the patch is the instructor's name, either as "JOHN DOE" or "J.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] DOE." Non-instructor students may wear a uniform with "TAEKWONDO" and an ATA patch on the back, however, these students do not wear their names on their backs.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Instead of a name, the student will have the location of the dojang.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Certified tournament judges may wear their appropriate level chevrons on their left sleeves.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Also, there is a black and red dobok used specifically for the leadership program, with red lettering and no patches.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Masters wear traditional silk uniforms for special events such as the Masters Ceremony at World Championships.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] At promotional testings and ATA tournaments, Level 3 Certified Instructors have the option to wear navy blue suits in lieu of their doboks.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] 5th degree black belts and up wear matching blue pants, while 1st through 4th degree black belts wear grey pants.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] A special ATA patch is worn on the instructor's left breast.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] In the 2019 Tournament season they also released an Adidas black and white dobok.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] The Songahm Taekwondo Federation is a branch of ATA established for South America.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Founded during the fall of 1990, The World Traditional Taekwondo Union (WTTU) is a division of Songahm Taekwondo.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] While the ATA consists of taekwondo schools in the United States and the STF consists of schools in South America, the WTTU covers the remainder of the world.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Within the Songahm system of taekwondo, there has been traditionally one 9th Degree Black Belt within the organization at a time.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] This individual held the title of Grand Master and was considered to be the leader of Songahm Taekwondo.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] After 2015, with the promotion of a second concurrent 9th Degree (Richard Reed), the title "Presiding Grand Master" is now used to indicate the Grand Master chosen from among the group of 9th degrees to be in charge of the martial arts side of ATA.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Lee was promoted to Grand Master in 1990, he created an informal council of "his most loyal and trusted Masters and advisors." This council consisted of Soon Ho Lee (H.U.'s brother and successor), In Ho Lee (Soon Ho's successor), G.K.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Lee (In Ho's successor), Robert Allemier, William Clark, and M.K.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] With his diagnosis of cancer in 2000, H.U.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Lee realized it was necessary to formalize his founder's council and thus "communicate his vision to the other seniors in the organization".
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Via his Grand Master's Decree on September 9, 2000, the Master's Council was created with the following members: Grandmasters Clark, In Ho Lee, G.K.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Lee, Robert Jager, Michael Caruso, and Cesar Ozuna (with whom H.U.
[src:combat-sport/ata-taekwondo] Lee had founded the South American branch).
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] A **combat sport**, or **fighting sport**, is a contact sport that usually involves one-on-one combat.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] In many combat sports, a contestant wins by scoring more points than the opponent, submitting the opponent with a hold, disabling the opponent (*knockout*, KO), or attacking the opponent in a specific or designated technique.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] Combat sports share a long history with the martial arts.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] Traditional styles of wrestling exist in most cultures; wrestling can be considered a cultural universal.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] Boxing contests date back to ancient Sumer in the 3rd millennium BCE and ancient Egypt *circa* 1350 BCE.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] The ancient Olympic Games included several combat-related sports: armored foot races, boxing, wrestling, and pankration, which was introduced in the Olympic Games of 648 BCE.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] In ancient China, combat sport appeared in the form of lei tai.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] It was a no-holds barred combat sport that combined boxing and wrestling.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] There is evidence of similar combat sports in ancient Egypt, India and Japan.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] Through the Middle Ages and Renaissance, the tournament was popular.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] Tournaments were competitions that featured several mock combat events, with jousting as a main event.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] While the tournament was popular among aristocrats, combat sports were practiced by all levels of society.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] The German school of late medieval martial arts distinguished sportive combat (*schimpf*) from serious combat (*ernst*).
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] In the German Renaissance, sportive combat competitions were known as Fechtschulen, corresponding to the Prize Playing in Tudor England.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] Out of these Prize Playing events developed the English boxing (or *prizefighting*) of the 18th century, which evolved into modern boxing with the introduction of the Marquess of Queensberry rules in 1867.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] Amateur boxing has been part of the modern Olympic Games since their introduction in 1904.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] Professional boxing became popular in the United States in the 1920s and experienced a "golden age" after World War II.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] Professional wrestling was once competitive catch wrestling, a legitimate combat sport in the late 19th and early 20th century, however it has since evolved into athletic theater.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] The creation of Brazilian jiu-jitsu is attributed to the Gracie family of Brazil in 1925 after Asian martial arts were introduced to Brazil.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] Vale-tudo, wrestling, Muay Thai kickboxing and luta livre gained popularity.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] Modern Muay Thai was developed in the 1920s to 1930s.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] Sambo was introduced in the Soviet Union.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] Modern Taekwondo also emerged after the Japanese occupation of Korea and became an Olympic sport in 2000.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] Sanshou as part of modern wushu was developed in the People's Republic of China in the 1950s.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] Kickboxing and full contact karate were developed in the 1960s and became popular in Japan and the West during the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] Modern MMA developed out of the interconnected subcultures of Vale Tudo and shoot wrestling.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] It was introduced in Japan in the form of Shooto in 1985, and in the United States as Ultimate Fighting Championship (UFC) in 1993.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] The Unified Rules of Mixed Martial Arts were introduced in 2000, and the sport experienced peak popularity in the 2000s.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] During this period, multiple brands and promotions were established.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] The most well-known promotion for MMA is UFC.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] Combat sports are generally more popular among men as athletes and spectators.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] For many years, participation in combat sports was practically exclusive to men; USA Boxing had a ban on women's boxing until 1993.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] A study conducted by Greenwell, Hancock, Simmons, and Thorn in 2015 revealed that combat sports had a largely male audience.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] The techniques used can be categorized into three domains: striking, grappling, and weapon usage, with some hybrid rule-sets combining striking and grappling.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] In weapon based sports, the weapons used are made to be non-lethal by means of modifying the striking portions of the weapon and requiring participants to wear protective clothing/armor.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] In combat sports, victory is obtained from blows, punches or attacks to the head to a point of physical injury that the opponent is unable to continue.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] Different forms of combat sport have different rules and regulations into the equipment competitors have to wear.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] In Amateur boxing seen at the Olympics, competitors are permitted to wear head guards and correctly weighted padded gloves, mouth guards are optional and the canvas floor protection from a hard fall.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] In sports such as Taekwondo, competitors are permitted to wear a trunk protector, head guard, gloves, groin guard and shin and forearm pads.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] Professional boxing and MMA are two of the most dangerous combat sports in the world due to the lack of protective gear worn (compared to the protected fists).
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] Competitors in these two sports have the option to wear a mouthguard and must wear suitable gloves.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] The lack of protective clothing makes competitors vulnerable to concussions and further traumatic head injuries.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] A scientific experiment, conducted in 2015 by Dr Andrew McIntosh of ACRISP at the Federation University of Australia, tested the impact of seven different head guards in combat sport.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] The results of the experiment revealed the benefits of the combination of a glove and headguard in maximising the impact energy attenuation.
[src:combat-sport/combat-sport] This means that injury rates are drastically lowered when protective gear is used.
